Rates are expected to remain depressed this week at the money market as maturities from Open Market Operation (OMO) and Nigerian Treasury Bills are expected to hit the system with an inflow of N924.72 billion. Yield at the Treasury Bills market had dropped to around two per cent last week and is expected to remain low this week as N695.08 billion from OMO maturities and N229.64 maturities from Treasury Bills flow into the system. The Monetary Policy Committee of the Central Bank of Nigeria had on Friday raised the Cash Reserve Requirement to 27.5 per cent to curb the level of liquidity from maturing bills, leaving the Monetary Policy Rate unchanged in line with its drive to boost lending to the real sector. The Committee in a vote of nine to 11 members agreed to increase the Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR) by 500bps to 27.5 per cent while holding the MPR at 13.5 per cent, Liquidity Ratio at 30 per cent and Asymmetric corridor at +200bps/-500bps around the MPR. The CRR increase is expected to quarantine between N812.6 to N855.3 billion from the banks’ vaults given total deposits ranging from N16.2 to N17.1 trillion as at September 2019. Analysts at Cowry Assets Management Limited who welcomed the decision of the MPC to increase the CRR by 500 basis points said “this creates an outlet to ease built up pressure of increased financial system liquidity which was created by its restrictive OMO policies. “In doing so, and by not reviewing the MPC upwards, we feel the monetary authority remains in alignment with the fiscal authority’s goal to boost output growth, in part, by making credit available at affordable cost to real sector players. With expected N4 trillion OMO maturities over the first quarter of 2020, the Committee expects that the CRR increase should restrain system liquidity given that a large chunk of these maturities can no longer access the OMO market following the restrictions of Pension Fund Administrators (PFAs) and other local investors. It is expected that trading volumes will increase and yields will further trim in the NTB market with the maturities and analysts at Afrinvest West Africa say they do not expect any significant movement in the OMO rates as the CBN will likely mop-up maturities in the coming week. Last week, the CBN auctioned OMO bills worth N240.29 billion to partly mop up the matured OMO bills worth N433.76 billion. With the net inflows of N193.47 billion, Nigeria Interbank Offer Rates (NIBOR) moderated for all tenor buckets with the NIBOR for overnight, 1-month, 3-months and 6-months tenure buckets compressed to 3.61 per cent from 5.3 per cent, 8.07 per cent from 8.73 per cent, 8.09 per cent from 8.72 per cent and 8.60 per cent from 9.46 per cent respectively. At the Bond market, values of FGN bonds traded at the over-the-counter (OTC) segment appreciated for most maturities tracked amid renewed demand pressure as the Debt Management Office (DMO) sold bonds worth N409.99 billion through the 5-year, 12.75% FGN APR 2023 worth N29.30 billion, 10-year, 14.55% FGN APR 2029 worth N106.39 billion and 30-year, 14.80% FGN APR 2049 worth N274.30 billion respectively. With the increased liquidity at the money market, and low yields from other instruments in the market, , analysts say they  FGN bond prices to rise amid expected buy pressure at the OTC market.